voice_to_text: The assassin reached the elevator entrance and instantly sensed the danger coming from the woman behind her. As a seasoned killer, Lena knew those bodyguards posed no real threat. Took down two of them with lethal precision before stepping into the elevator. But the moment she entered, facial recognition cameras locked onto her. The elevator shot upward at high speed and abruptly halted on the 50th floor. Lena raised her gun, fully alert. Just as she expected, five armed guards were waiting outside. She moved toward the designated location and discovered several more hitmen who had been anticipating her arrival. At the center of the room lay the target of her mission, already executed by someone else. San Antonio, the mastermind behind the trap, stepped out to confront her. The entire operation had been orchestrated for one purpose to capture Lena. He offered her triple her usual fee if she agreed to join his organization. But Lena had never bowed to anyone. She detonated a fire extinguisher to create a smoke screen and sprinted away in the chaos. Enraged, Antonio immediately alerted the assassin stationed on the ground floor. As she reached the first level, Lena quickly eliminated several of them. But Antonio and his men were already closing in. Without hesitation, she slipped toward the parking area, jumped into a car, and sped away, vanishing before they could catch her.

During one of these week long vacations to Cancun, she ended up getting pregnant from one of the six hotel staff she cheated on me with. At this point, I was so over the relationship that I didn't care if it ended. After I moved out and moved back to my parents house, I got a call from an anonymous number. I told him whatever and for him and his crazy family to leave me alone. Truthfully, I was scared. Of him. I knew he had enough money to hire whoever he wanted to do whatever he wanted. I thought that he would help me, but instead he told me to put my hands behind my back and that I was being arrested. I demanded that he tell me why I was being arrested, but he told me to shut my broke ass up. The second he called me broke, I realized that this was all my ex's father I was doing. He paid the cop off to arrest me. At this point, I didn't even fight back. The cop put me in his cop car and just as I thought, he brought me to my ex girlfriend's estate. When he threw me out of the car, my girlfriend's father was waiting for me sipping tea like a James Bond villain. I asked him if he Was going to take my life away. And all he said was, we need to talk. I followed him inside and passed by my girlfriend who was getting her feet done. Her father sat me down and there was trembling in his voice. My babe.

I tipped my ex friend and bully as petty revenge. Back in high school, this guy named Brandon made my life absolute hell. For two years straight, he would knock my books out of my hands, trip me in the hallway, and steal my lunch money while laughing with his buddies. The worst part was, we used to be actual friends in middle school before he decided being popular was more important. He started hanging with the jocks, and suddenly I was his favorite target. Every single day, he found new ways to embarrass me. Once he poured chocolate milk on my white shirt right before my presentation in English class. Another time, he took my gym clothes and threw them in the toilet. Teachers never did anything because his dad donated money to the school. I spent those two years just trying to survive and stay invisible. After graduation, I moved three hours away for college and never looked back at all. Contact with everyone from that town started fresh. Made real friends. Got my degree in accounting. Life was actually good for once. Then last month, I was visiting my parents for Thanksgiving weekend. My mom wanted to order pizza for dinner because she was too tired to cook. She pulled up this app and ordered from the local pizza place. When the doorbell rang 30 minutes later, I opened it without thinking. Standing there in a greasy pizza delivery uniform holding our pepperoni and cheese was Brandon His face went pale when he recognized me. I just stood there frozen. He looked rough. His hair was thinning, he had bags under his eyes, and that confident smirk he always wore was completely gone. Hey, man, he said quietly, handing me the pizza boxes, that'll be 23 50. I could tell he was praying I wouldn't say anything. His hands were actually shaking a little as he held out the card reader. For a second I almost felt bad, but then I remembered the chocolate milk, the toilet, gym clothes, the two years of constant humiliation. So I pulled out my wallet and handed him a hundred dollar Bill. Keep the change, I said, loudly enough for my mom to hear from the kitchen. His eye

An email from my ex through our co parenting app. She informed me that the children had dentist appointments during my upcoming weekend and wouldn't be available until Sunday. I forwarded it to Catherine immediately. Catherine's response was swift. She filed a motion citing the judge's order about medical appointments requiring both parents consent. Within hours, my ex backtracked, claiming she'd made an error with the dates. Friday arrived with my usual pickup time. I sat in my car outside my ex's house watching the clock. Four PM came and went, no sign of the kids. I texted through the app, keeping everything documented. No response. At 4:30, I knocked on the door. My ex answered with a fake surprised expression. She claimed the kids were at a friend's birthday party and she'd forgotten to tell me. I asked for the address. She said she'd have to check and get back to me. I waited in my car documenting everything Catherine had warned me about these games. Stay calm, follow the process. Don't give them ammunition. An hour later, my ex emerged with the kids. They walked slowly, heads down, my daughter gripping her brother's hand. The drive to my house was silent. Jake stared out the window while my daughter clutched her backpack like a shield. At home, they went straight to their room without the usual excitement about weekend activities, made their favorite dinner, hoping to ease the tension. They picked at their food, exchanging worried glances when I asked about school. They gave one word answers. When I suggested a movie, they shook their heads. That night, I heard crying from their room. I found Jake curled up in his sister's bed, both of them trembling. I sat on the floor beside them, not wanting to crowd their space. Eventually, my daughter was.

What's the hardest part about being identical twins when only one of you is pretty? My twin sister Emma always got the compliments. Same face, same hair, same everything. But somehow I was the backup copy. Teachers would say things like, oh, you're Emma's sister when they met me. Boys would ask me to introduce them to Emma. Even our own grandma would mix up our names, then correct herself and say, oh, wait, you're the other one. The worst part was picture day in 7th grade. Mom made us wear matching blue dresses because she thought it would be adorable. We stood next to each other for the twin photo. And when the photographer looked through his camera, he actually moved me behind Emma. This way the lighting hits better, he said. I knew what he meant. Emma never noticed how differently people treated us. He'd bounce into rooms and everyone would light up. I'd follow behind and get polite smiles. When we turned 16, Dad took us car shopping. The salesman spent the whole time talking to Emma about features and colors. He asked me if I was getting a car, too, like I was just there for the ride. That summer, everything changed when Emma left for cheerleading camp. For two weeks, I was just me. I started wearing my hair differently, bought clothes Emma would never pick. Actually talk to people instead of letting her do all the talking. When Marcus from my chemistry class asked Me to hang out. I couldn't believe he was talking to me and not waiting for Emma to show up. We went to the movies and got burgers after he kept staring at me and I thought maybe something was wrong with my makeup. Finally he said, you know, you're way more interesting than your sister. I nearly choked on my drink. Emma's pretty.

The crackhead lunged at me so I turned him into a femboy and sold him on Etsy. I live in a sketchy little neighborhood where everyone minds their business except for this one dude. Let's call him Rico. Rico is, well, he's like a local cryptid. No one knows where he lives, but he appears at 3:00am yelling about government conspiracies, anime girls and how he once fought a raccoon with his bare hands. Classic Rico. Anyway, last night I'm walking back from the corner store with a bag of Hot Cheetos and chocolate milk living my best trashy life when out of nowhere Rico lunges at me like a feral possum in heat. He's screaming something about me stealing his aura. At this point my fight or flight kicked in and apparently my brain chose black magic. See, I've been dabbling in some alternative arts lately. Long story short, I had a transformation Hex saved on my notes app. Don't ask why, just accept it. So mid lunch I screamed the words, clap my hands together and suddenly, poof, Rico is no longer Rico. Rico is now Rianna pink crop top, cat ears, thigh high socks, eyeliner sharper than my credit score, the full Femboy starter pack. He blinks, I blink. We both stand there for a solid five seconds like, did that just happen? Fast forward to today and uh, I may have listed him on Etsy under Handcrafted Chaos Beings. Someone from Portland bought him within 3 Minutes for 275 plus shipping. Now I'm sitting here sipping my chocolate milk, trying to process the fact that I may have invented a new side hustle. Before anyone asks, yes, Rico. Now Rihanna is thriving. The buyer sent me pics. He's got a made outfit. Now I don't know how to feel.

People who grew up rich. When did you realise you were living in a bubble and not like everyone else? I thought every kid had their birthdays planned by event coordinators. Until I was 13, every April, my parents would rent out country clubs or these fancy rooftop venues downtown. They'd hire magicians, ice cream trucks, face painters, and once even this guy who brought parrots that could talk. I'm talking like 60 kids from school showing up, tables covered in those fancy cloth things, waiters walking around with little appetizers on trays. But here's the weird part. None of the kids ever stayed long. Like they'd show up, eat some cake, watch the magic show for maybe an hour, then their parents would collect them and they'd leave. And nobody ever brought me actual presents, just these white envelopes that my mom would grab and stuff into her purse before I could even see what was inside. I didn't think it was strange back then. Figured that's just how birthdays worked. The envelopes probably had money or gift cards or something, right? And maybe other kids just had smaller parties because their parents weren't as organised as mine. Then in 7th grade, this kid, Jake, from my math class, invited me to his birthday party. I was actually pretty excited because Jake was cool and I wanted to be friends with him. My mom dropped me off at this public park and I was confused because there was no Ballet or anything, just regular parking spots. When I found Jake's party, my brain basically short circuited. There was one folding table with a plastic tablecloth, hot dogs cooking on this little portable grill and a cooler full of sodas. No servers, no fancy decorations, just balloons tied to the table legs. Get this, there was one soccer ball. That was it for entertainment. But all the kids were laughing their heads off. They were playing tag, kicking the soccer ball around and having these intense conversations about video games and t V shows. Everyone had wrapped presents, actual gifts and colourful paper with ribbons and stuff. Jake opened each one and got genuinely excited about things like Pokemon cards and a new skateboard. The party lasted four hours. Four hours. And nobody wanted to leave. Parents had to literally drag their kids away because it was.

The friendship is solid when y'all don't even go to the same school and it doesn't matter. Like, bro, real friends don't need to be in the same classroom or even the same postcode to stay tight. You could be across the city in a different uniform, learning completely different subjects, but somehow the bond never fades. Everyone else is like, oh, if you don't go to the same school, you'll drift apart. Nah, bro, not us. I could be sitting in math class stressed out over equations I'll never use in life, and you're across town doing science experiments, and we're still texting dumb memes like we saw each other five minutes ago. And when we do link up on the weekend, it's like we never left. No awkward vibes, no weird energy, just straight vibes. Bro, we might not be in the same school, but we've got the same mindset, same humor, same jokes, same energy. And the best part? When you meet their school friends and suddenly you feel famous, like, oh, you're that friend they always talk about. Yeah, that's me. I don't even go here, but I run this friendship. So if you've got a friend that's in another school but still feels closer than anyone in your class, appreciate that. That's real friendship. Forget proximity. It's about loyalty.

Same dates, same amount of money, but at least I'd be with someone who actually valued my time. Maya found out through our mutual friend Jenna. She called me eight times in a row. I declined. Every single one. Finally, she texted, withdrawing the money is so petty. You're punishing me for having other friends. I didn't respond. Two days later, Maya's texting the group chat. Her dad just got a new job offer in Texas. They're moving in three weeks. She wants one last big hang out with everyone before she leaves. Maybe a beach day or that new escape room downtown, whatever we want. Everyone's replying with sad emojis and Omg, no. And we have to do.

This is inappropriate. This is alerting. He seemed genuinely surprised. Said if it bothered me that much, he'd stop. For exactly four weeks, it stopped. Then it started again. Gradually. A text here and there. Then every evening again, I confronted him. This time he came home the next day with her to clear the air. She sat on our couch talking, making jokes about how I must have trust issues, how if I felt threatened by their friendship, that was my problem, not hers. She even winked at him when she said it. The second she left, I told him I never wanted to see or hear about her again. That if he'd rather have her as a friend than me as a wife, he should just say it. He promised it was over. Said he'd barely talk to her. Work. Only two weeks later, we left for our anniversary trip to Santorini. Three weeks, just us. It supposed to fix everything. Except she texted him two to three times every single day. I'd see his phone light up. Autumn, autumn, autumn. He'd wait until I was in the shower to respond, or when I fell asleep. Once I woke up at 2:00am and he was on the balcony typing away. When I asked about it, he said she was having marriage problems, that she needed someone to talk to. Are you a marriage counselor now? I asked. Laughed it off. We got home with one week of vacation. Left. He suggested dinner and a movie. I agree. We needed it. We were at the restaurant, finally having a good time when she walked in with her husband. She spotted us, immediately came over. Oh, my god, what a coincidence. Do you guys wanna join us? I said yes before my husband could say no. She was so pleasant. Touching my husband's arm while asking about Santa

Something I replied exactly how she'd expect. Can't make it. Already have plans that weekend. The group chat went quiet for a minute. Then Maya, what plans? Just plans. You know how it is. She started typing, stopped, typed again. Finally, can you please just come? This is important. So was New York. Jenna texted me privately, dude, she's moving. Can you just let it go? I told Jenna the same thing I've been thinking for weeks. Some people only care about your time when it's convenient for them. Maya called me seven times that night, texted, this is the last time you'll see me for years. And you're really gonna do this over one trip I sent back. You already showed me how you prioritize friendships. I'm just matching your energy. You taught me that childhood friends matter more than current ones, right? Well, I'm spending that day with my cousin. We've known each other since we were babies. She didn't reply. Three days later, her family moved. I didn't go to the goodbye party her mom threw. Haven't heard from Maya since. I went to Seattle. Had an amazing time. Didn't think about her once last week. Six months later, I found out from someone's Instagram story that Chelsea never even went to New York with her. Chelsea cancelled two days before the trip because her ex boyfriend wanted to get back together. Maya ended up going alone, posted one sad selfie in Times Square and came home early.

My best friend cancelled our one year long plan because her childhood best friend told her to. So I matched her energy. We've been saving for this trip to New York since junior year. Maya and I made a pact the night we watched the ball drop on TV, we'd be there in person for New Year's 2024. Every weekend shift at the diner, every birthday check from relatives, every dollar we could scrape together went into our shared savings account. By may, we had two thousand hundred and forty seven dollars. Taylor Swift tickets, Broadway shows, the works. I'll never forget the day we hit $2,000. First. Maya called me screaming and we spent three hours planning every detail, which hotel, which restaurants, even which subway lines we take. I had a whole notebook dedicated to the, she had a Pinterest board with 400 pins. Three weeks before we're supposed to leave, Maya text me at eleven PM on a Tuesday. So Chelsea really wants to go to NYC for her birthday and she asked if I'd come with her instead. You understand, right? Chelsea, her childhood best friend from elementary school who moved to California in eighth grade. They see each other maybe twice a year when Chelsea visits her grandparents. But every single time I become invisible, Maya cancels and ditches our group, acts like the rest of us don't exist and I'm supposed to just understand because they have history. I stared at that message for 10 minutes. My Mom asked me what was wrong, and I couldn't even explain it. Finally, I typed back, do whatever you want, she replied immediately, paragraphs.

I want a divorce. After nine months of marriage? Am I being immature? My husband and I have been together for four years. I love him even now. But three months ago, something happened that I can't get past. I surprised him at his office with lunch. That's when I met autumn, his colleague. They were laughing at his desk. And when I walked in, there was this weird pause, like I'd interrupted something. He introduced us, said they've been working together for five years. Five years? And I'd never heard her name. Not once. On the drive home, I asked why he never mentioned her. He said, we rarely talk about work since I don't understand his field. That stuck with me, the way he said it. That night, I started paying attention. He was on his phone constantly, smiling at texts, typing quick responses. During dinner, during movies, even when we were in bed. A week later, I asked him directly, who are you texting so much? He didn't hesitate. He unlocked his phone and handed it to me. See for yourself. I scrolled through their messages. It was pages and pages of daily conversations, cute nicknames, inside jokes. Her complaining about her husband, asking intimate questions about our relationship, about me. Then I found the one that made my stomach drop. My husband's birthday is June 14. I threw him a party. Friends, family, everything. At nine forty seven PM that night, she texted, you must be Bored at your own party, or you wouldn't be texting me instead of being with her. He was texting her at the party. I spent two weeks planning for him. I looked on the phone.

Then I checked through the bedroom door and he was still asleep. So I hauled six grocery bags into the kitchen as quietly as humanly possible. Every plastic bag sounded like a firecracker. I hid everything in the cabinet we never use, the one above the fridge. Then I called his best friend, Griffin, and begged him to take my husband out of the day. I need at least six hours, I said. Griffin asked why, and I just said, trust me, I'll explain later. He showed up at noon and they left to go to some car show two towns over. The second the door closed, I pulled out every pot we owned. His mom stayed on Facetime with me for the first hour, walking me through the marination process. More yogurt, she kept saying. No more. You need at least two cups. Trust me, I've been making this for 35 years. I started cooking at one PM the recipe said medium heat, but our stove runs hot and I didn't adjust. The first batch burned because I had the heat too high and I panicked when I smelled it. I dumped the entire pot in the sink and watched $60 worth of chicken and spices go down the drain. The second batch looked promising until I realised the rice was mushy, completely overcooked. I'd left it on for three minutes too long while I was answering his mom's call and the whole thing was ruined. Another $40 Wasted. I sat on the kitchen floor at four PM and just stared at the ceiling for 10 minutes. I been cooking for three hours straight and I had nothing to show for it except two pots of wasted food and turmeric stains on literally every dish towel we own. My hands smelled like garam masala. There was rice stuck to my shirt. My back hurt from standing. I.

Ipads, factory reset, wiped everything, put them back in their original boxes with the chargers and screen protectors, all neat. I even found the little instruction booklets that came with them, set them on the kitchen table, ready to list on Facebook Marketplace. But I couldn't do it. I kept looking at those boxes thinking about how excited they were when they first got them last Christmas. How my daughter would sit on my lap while we played puzzle games together, how my son would show me his drawings, so proud of the little dinosaurs he made on the art app. I put the boxes in a cardboard box, shove them in the back of my bedroom closet behind some old blankets, told myself I'd decide later. Summer ended, school started, and something weird happened. My kids actually started getting along. Maybe it was being back in routine. Maybe they just needed to mature a little. Maybe it was losing those tablets that did it. But they started sharing again, playing board games together after dinner, building Lego sets without fighting over pieces. September turned into October, then November. By the time Thanksgiving rolled around, my kids were like different people. They set the table together without being asked. My son helped my daughter with her spelling homework. I caught them laughing at some inside joke in the hallway one morning and it hit me that I hadn't heard them laugh together in months before the ipads got taken. Then December came and reality set in. Money was tight this year, like really tight. My hours got cut at work. Car needed new brakes. The water heater broke and had to be replaced. Every time I thought about Christmas, my stomach hurt. I sat down one.

I said yes before my husband could say no. She was so pleasant, touching my husband's arm while asking about Santorini, laughing at his jokes. Her husband barely said a word. Then I asked loud enough for everyone to hear. So how are things with you two? I heard you've been having marriage problems. Her husband's face went white. What? Who said that? My husband did. He showed me all your texts about it. The table went silent. Autumn stared at my husband. Her husband stared at her. My husband tried to backtrack. Stammered something about misunderstanding. I smiled and said, oh, I'm sorry if I got it wrong. I just assumed since you were texting him multiple times a day on our vacation. Autumn looked like she wanted to kill him. When we got home, he exploded. Said I was out of line, that I humiliated him. I asked him one question. Have you ever slept with her? He went quiet. Then once, before I even met you, I told him I wanted a divorce. Said at minimum they were having an emotional affair. Called me silly. Said I was overreacting to text with a friend. That was two weeks ago. I've refused all physical contact since. I work late, go to the gym, take long walks. I eat dinner alone at restaurants or the library. When I come home, I shower and go straight to bed. My mother thinks I'm making a big fuss over nothing. His parents Called me immature. He's begging for marriage counseling, offering to quit his job, move cities, anything. But my gut is screaming that something is very, very wrong. And I've Learned to trust my gut.

Overcooked. I left it on for three minutes too long while I was answering his mom's call and the whole thing was ruined. Another $40 wasted. I sat on the kitchen floor at four PM and just stared at the ceiling for 10 minutes. I've been cooking for three hours straight and I had nothing to show for it except two pots of wasted food and turmeric stains on literally every dish towel we own. My hands smelled like garam masala. There was rice stuck to my shirt. My back hurt from standing. I wanted to give up and just order take out. But then I remembered his voice last night, that sad whatever, like he'd accepted he'd never have it again. So I got up and I started batch No. 3. This time I set timers for everything, phone timer, oven timer, even the microwave timer as backup. I watched that pot like my life depended on it. I checked the rice every 90 seconds with a fork. I followed his mom's instructions exactly, measuring everything twice using actual measuring cups instead of eyeballing it. At 6:15, the rice was perfect. The chicken was tender and falling off the bone. The saffron had turned everything this or just golden color. And the whole house smelled exactly like his childhood home, like his mom's kitchen on the wallie. I plated everything in our nicest serving dish and covered it with oil to keep it warm. Griffin just texted me. They're 20 minutes away. I'm standing in our kitchen right now surrounded by every dirty pot and pan we own. There's spices all over the counter. I have turmeric under my fingernails that won't come out. I used $40 worth of saffron in one dish and I'm still not sure I used enough. But the biryani looks incredible. It smells perfect. And in 20 minutes, my husband is going to walk through that door and smell his mom's cooking for the first time in over a year. I'm terrified this won't taste right. I'm terrified he'll take one bite and know it's wrong. But I'm also hoping that even if it's not perfect, he'll understand that I woke up before sunrise and drove four hours and spent seven hours cooking because I love him. The garage door just opened. He's home.

Night after the kids were in bed and looked at my bank account, looked at my credit card, did the math. The gifts I could actually afford would fit in a shoebox, maybe two. I wanted to cry. My kids have been so good. They'd earned something special this year, but I just didn't have it. Then I remembered the closet, the boxes, the ipads. I dug them out that night, dusted off the cardboard box they've been sitting in, opened up each iPad box and checked that everything was still there. Chargers, cable screen, still perfect. They looked brand new. I wrapped them the next day while the kids were at school. Use the nicest wrapping paper we had, the shiny red kind with little gold stars, a big bows out of curling ribbon, put their names on fancy gift tags. On Christmas morning, there were only four presents under the tree, two for each kid. One was a pair of pajamas for each of them. The other was the wrapped iPad boxes. My daughter opened hers first. She ripped through the paper and then just stopped, stared at the box. She looked up at me with this confused expression. Wait, she said, is this my iPad? I nodded, but you said you sold them. My son said he was holding his box now, not even opening it yet. I told them the truth. I said I couldn't do it. I put them away instead and I told them The reason they were getting them back is because they showed me they earned them all those months of being good to each other, helping around the house, no fighting. That's what got them back. My daughter tackled me in a hug so hard I almost fell off the couch. My son just sat there for a second then said, so we were basically on a six month test.

My husband is going to be either pleasantly or unpleasantly surprised when he gets home. I overheard him last night on the phone with his friend saying, I just really miss my mom's biryani, you know, then he went quiet and said, but we can't get the ingredients here. So whatever, that, whatever broke something in me. We're both first gen Indian Americans and since we got married last year, we've been living off chicken and rice because the nearest Indian grocery store is two hours away. I didn't realize how much he missed home until I heard his voice crack talking to his friend. So I made a plan. I set my alarm for 4:30 this morning while he was still asleep. I grabbed the grocery list. His mom texted me at midnight after I called her crying and I just drove. The GPS said two hours and 12 minutes one way. The store opened at 7. I got there at six, 45 and sat in the parking lot watching the sun come up, trying not to think about how I've never made biryani in my entire life. My hands were shaking when I grabbed my coffee. When the doors finally opened, I walked in and immediately felt lost. Just store was huge and everything was labeled in three different languages. I called his mom from aisle three, standing there with my list and she walked me through finding every single ingredient. Dasmati, rice, saffron, $40 for a container. Smaller than my thumb. He got it. Cardamom pods that I had to count out myself. The spices alone cost me 80.

I was like, okay, sure, whatever. Fast forward to last week, me and my husband decided to throw a little BBQ at our place. Nothing crazy, just some friends, some burgers, some drinks. My husband invited Mary. I specifically told him I didn't want her there because she makes me uncomfortable. He said he had another talk with her and she understood and promised she wouldn't say anything weird this time. So I said fine. The BBQ was actually going pretty well. Mary showed up and was being normal for once, grilled stuff, people were drinking, playing music in the backyard. By midnight, most people had left and there were only like four of us still hanging out in our living room. I was walking past the couch carrying a glass of red wine when I tripped over the edge of our carpet, like a full stumble and the wine went flying right onto Mary's jeans. I immediately started apologizing. Oh my god, I'm so sorry. Let me get you some paper towels. I'll pay for the dry cleaning. I'm so sorry. Mary just stared at her jeans. Then she looked up at me. You did that on purpose? I was like, what? No, I literally tripped. You saw me trip? She stood up and her face was getting red. You're a witch. You've always been a witch. This is part of some ritual, isn't it? I thought she was joking at first, so I kind of nervous laughed bad Move. Don't laugh at me, she said. I know what you're doing. You're trying to ruin my life. You've been trying to ruin my friendship with your husband ever since you showed up.

Morning. I asked him what this was. He said he finally got to upgrade his setup like he'd been wanting to for months. I asked him where he got the money. He said from our account. I said that was my bonus. He said, yeah, and now we have a nice new gaming system. I told him I wanted to use that money for myself. I told him about my purse and my shoes. I told him I had been looking forward to finally getting something nice after carrying us financially for years. He rolled his eyes. He actually rolled his eyes at me. He said I was being selfish. He said I should be happy that he finally got to achieve his dream of having a nice gaming setup. He called me spoiled for being upset that I couldn't spend my own money on myself first. I lost it. I called him an ungrateful jerk. I asked him why he deserved new stuff when I was the one who had been providing for both of us. I I asked him what exactly he had contributed in the last few years. I asked him when the last time he even applied for a job was. He got really quiet. His face went red. He didn't have an answer because there wasn't one. He just stood there with his new controller in his hand, not saying anything. Then he stormed off to the bedroom. I heard him on the phone with Someone About 20 minutes later, he came out with a bag packed. He said he was going to stay with his family for a while. They live about an hour away. He said he didn't feel supported in his own home. I didn't even try to stop him. I just stood there and watched him walk out the door.

My husband stood up and was like, Mary, calm down. It was an accident. But she wasn't listening. She was on a roll. Now she's an immigrant Gypsy trying to poison you against me. Can't you see that? She's been doing witchcraft or whatever they do over there. That's why you don't invite me over as much anymore. She's got you under some kind of spell. I started crying, not like sobbing, but tears were coming down my face because this was so out of nowhere and so mean and I didn't understand where it was coming from. Mary, I'm so sorry about the wine. Please let me shut up, she said. Just shut up. You don't belong here. You never did. The other two people in the room were just frozen. Nobody knew what to do. My husband tried to step in again, but Mary kept going, talking about how I've been manipulating everyone and how she was the only one who could see through me. Something in me just snapped. Get out, I said. Mary stopped mid sentence. Excuse me. Get out of my house right now. She laughed. You can't kick me out. This is your husband's house, too. I looked at my husband. He nodded at me, Mary, you need to leave. She looked between us like she couldn't believe what was happening. Then she grabbed her purse off the couch and walked to the door. Before she left, she turned around and pointed at me. You're going to regret this. All of you are going to see what she really is. Then she slammed the door. The room was dead silent for like a full minute. My husband came over and hugged me. The other two people quietly said they should probably head out and left. After they were gone, I told my husband that Mary is never allowed in our house again, ever. He didn't argue.

My sister told me to control my woman. I couldn't stop laughing. So my wife, Mina, she's the kind of woman who turns heads wherever she goes, always glowing, always put together like she's walking out of a magazine, even if she's just running to grab milk. She loves fashion. She loves herself and she owns it. My sister, Betty, the complete opposite. She's the women belong in the kitchen type. Think floral apron, husband's dinner on the table by 6. I die for anyone who doesn't fit her idea of a lady. We don't talk much, and honestly, that's by design. Every time we do, she finds a way to throw shade at Mina. Like if Mina wears a sundress, Betty will go, well, at least she's dressed like a woman today. But if Mina wears something fitted or modern, it's, wow, that's a little revealing for family, don't you think? Mina just laughs. She's got that kind of laugh that makes you think she's unbothered, the kind that kills with Grace. But me, I'm counting to 10 in my head every time. Anyway, Eddie got pregnant and when she invited us to her formal dinner to celebrate, I thought maybe, just maybe, we could be civil. Mina wore this dark green tailored suit, sleek and powerful. It wasn't revealing, wasn't flashy, just elegant. She looked like money, like power, like everything Betty could never be. We get to the door, Betty opens it and her face drops like She just saw a ghost. She forces a smile and says, are you really wearing that? Mina? Cool as ever goes. Yes, you said formal, right? Inside, it's obvious Betty's been rehearsing her judgment all week. She's whispering behind her wine glass, smirking to my aunts, giving me those fake smiles that mean I'm about to talk shit. Every time Mina walks by, Betty's eyes roll like clockwork. At one point, she cracks this joke loud enough for everyone to hear. Guess, Mina, where's the pants in your marriage, huh? Poor you, stuck wearing all the pink frilly dresses. Everyone laughs awkwardly. Mina squeezes my hand under the table and whispers, don't, not tonight. I nod. I try to breathe. I try to focus on anything else, the candles, the baby photos, the sound of my jaw clenching. And Betty stands up, glass in hand, like to make a toast, she says. She starts soft, thanking everyone, talking about motherhood, family, all that sentimental crap. Then her tone shifts. Her smile fades. Her voice gets that sharp, sugary edge. She looks straight at Mina and says, it's hard raising a daughter in a world where women want to act and dress like men. She pauses, eyes locked on my wife like a sniper sight. The devil often hides in those closest to us. If you can spot him, don't let him into your home. The table goes dead silent. You could hear a pin drop. Everyone's eyes flick between them. Mina's calm face and Betty's smug little grin. Mina doesn't say a word. She just pushes her chair back, hands up, and walks out. No scene, no words, just this quiet dignity that somehow felt louder than Betty's entire speech. And me, I follow her. I don't even look back. Later that night, my phone blows up. My.

At Thanksgiving dinner, my sister stood up and announced, we voted and you're not family anymore. Everyone nodded. I said okay and left. Three days later, the bank called them. I was carving the Turkey when my sister Melissa clinked her fork against her wine glass. The room went quiet. We need to discuss something as a family, she said, looking directly at me. We took a vote last week. You're not part of this family anymore. I set down the carving knife slowly around the table. My parents nodded. My brother, Josh, avoided eye contact. My other sister, Emma, was recording on her phone. Even my grandmother folded her napkin and muttered, it's for the best. You voted me out of the family, I asked. It was unanimous, my father said. You never fit in anyway. Different values, different priorities. You're always working, never here for family events. I missed three dinners in five years. You didn't come to Emma's gender reveal party, Melissa added, I was performing emergency surgery. Exactly, my mother said. You think you're better than us with your doctor job and your fancy hospital. We're simple people. You don't belong here. Josh finally spoke. Plus, you never help with family expenses. I was fixing my plate when my mom casually asked, have you picked which family you're moving in with after Friday? I froze mid scoop. What are you talking about? She didn't even look up from her phone. Your dad and I are getting divorced. We're selling the house. You have until Friday to decide who you want to live with. I was 17. They've been fighting for months, but I didn't think it was this bad. That night, I tried talking to my dad. He was in the garage packing boxes. Dad, what's going on? He finally stopped and looked at me. Your mom and I agreed. You're old enough to choose. No pressure. But there was pressure. My mom kept making comments about how Dad's new apartment was smaller. My dad mentioned Mom's boyfriend was moving in next month. Wait, boyfriend? Yeah, dad said, not meeting my eyes. Marcus. They met at her office. I felt sick. How long does it matter? He went back to packing. Next day, I confronted my mom. She was in her bedroom sorting through old photos and I noticed she was only keeping the ones without my dad in them. Marcus and I have been together for 4 months, she admitted. But your father knew we were already separated emotionally. Four months. The house went up for sale six months ago. Her face changed. Your father told you that? That's when I found the real estate listing on her laptop. She listed The house eight months ago, before the fights even started. I went back to my dad that night. When did you actually find out about Marcus? He was silent for a long time. Then he pulled out his phone and showed me a text. Red. My mom had been planning to leave for over a year. The messages went back to when I was 16. But it got worse. There was a message from my mom to Marcus that said, just need to wait until the life insurance policy matures in November. Then we can be together. My blood went cold. Dad, what life insurance policy? His face went pale. I took one out three years ago. Your mom's the beneficiary. It matures next week. Friday, I whispered. The same day they wanted me to choose. The same day they were finalizing everything. That night, I couldn't sleep. I kept thinking about how eager my mom had been for me to choose. How she kept.

While I was scrolling TikTok, I saw my boyfriend in someone else's boyfriend reveal. Not just any reveal, either. This girl had 400,000 followers, and the video already had 2 million views. There was Kalani, my boyfriend of three years, kissing her in front of the Eiffel Tower with the caption, finally showing you guys my man. Together six months. My hands went numb. Kalani was supposed to be in Phoenix for a medical conference. I checked his Instagram. He posted a photo of a conference room 12 hours ago. But the meta data on her TikTok showed it was filmed yesterday in Paris. I screenshotted everything before my brain could talk me out of it. Then I went to her profile. Hundreds of videos of them together. Date nights, cooking videos, morning routines. The cooking videos were filmed in an apartment I didn't recognize. But I saw Kalani's watch on the counter, the one I'd bought him for his birthday. My stomach churned as I kept scrolling. Three months ago, she posted about meeting his parents. Same weekend he told me he was visiting his sick college roommate. There was a photo of her with his mom and dad at their anniversary dinner. The dinner I wasn't invited to because it was family only. I called him immediately. He answered on the second ring, casual as ever. Hey, Babe. Conference is pretty boring. Missing you. My voice came out steady somehow. How's Phoenix? Hot and full of old doctors. Can't Wait to come home tomorrow. I pulled up her TikTok of them at a French cafe. Posted an hour ago. That's funny, because Phoenix looks a lot like Paris on TikTok. Silence. Then what are you talking about? Adele Moreau. Ring a bell? Your girlfriend with 400 K followers who's been posting videos of you two for six months. He hung up. I called back. Straight to voicemail. I was typing a text when my phone rang. Unknown number with a French country code. I answered. You're the other woman. Her accent was slight but noticeable. Adele. Excuse me? Kalani told me about you months ago. His ex, who could. Didn't let go. He said you were stalking him. That's why he had to be careful about posting our relationship. The audacity of this man. I'm not his ex. We live together. We have a lease together. I just helped him pay for his mom's surgery. She laughed, bitter and sharp. His mom's surgery? His mother hasn't been sick a day in her life. I had dinner with her last night. She keeps asking when we're getting married. My head spun. Send me proof. Within minutes, my phone flooded with photos. Then with his parents, who I've been told didn't approve of me.

Benjamin, Week 3, I found him crying in the garage at 2:00am. He said watching me stay calm proved I didn't love him anymore, that if I really cared, I would have been devastated, would have checked his phone, would have confronted this Jade person. I asked him if he wanted me to take a breakdown to make him feel better. He didn't answer. His mom called last week. Apparently he told her I had zero emotional reaction when he tested our marriage. She said maybe I was depressed and I needed professional help. I told her maybe her son shouldn't play stupid games if he can't handle the results. She hung up on me. Now he's refusing couples therapy, says there's no point if I'm this cold and unfeeling, that he needs a wife who actually shows emotions. I reminded him I show plenty of emotions. I cried watching our son's school play last month. I laughed at his jokes just last week. I get excited about things but not about losing me. He said, I'm not losing you. I said you're still here. You're just mad. I didn't panic. Yesterday morning, our 5 year old asked why daddy doesn't kiss mommy goodbye anymore. I didn't know what to say.

I thought I was straight, but I think I've fallen in love with my best friend. Every night at exactly eleven forty seven PM, he sends the same text. Good night, bro, love you. We were at his house playing video games and he just casually said, love you, man. When I left, I thought about it the entire drive home. My hands were shaking on the steering wheel. After that, the text start every single night. Even when he was on vacation with his family. Even when I knew he was at parties. 11:47 p m. Like clockwork. I tried dating girls to prove I was normal. Went out with Samantha from my English class twice. She was nice, pretty, into me. When she tried to kiss me in her car, I panicked and said I had to go because my mom was calling. He was lying on the couch reading his history notes out loud, and I was on the floor pretending to take notes, but really just watching him. The way he bites his lip when he's concentrating. Instead, I sat there frozen. As he shifted, his head landed on my shoulder. I didn't move for two hours. My entire left side went numb. My leg fell asleep so bad I had pins and needles. I told her she had two choices, sleep in the tent tonight or lose her phone until Christmas break was over. She picked the tent. She kept trying to negotiate. Can I at least come in to use the bathroom? Yes. Can I get water? Yes. Can I come in if it rains? I told her the tent was waterproof and she'd be fine. I slept in the room right next to the back door so I could hear if anything went wrong, set three alarms to check on her throughout the night. Around 11, I heard her unzip the tent and run inside to pee. She was shivering, even though it wasn't that cold yet. Around 2 in the morning, I checked through the window and saw her curled up in the sleeping bag. 5:30, the bird started going crazy and I heard her groan. When I opened the back door at 7, she was already awake. Her hair was a mess and her eyes were red. Mom, can I please come inside now? Her voice cracked. I told her to come in and she practically ran. To the bathroom. When she came to the kitchen, I made her hot chocolate. She wrapped both hands around the mug and stared at it. It was horrible, she said quietly. The mat was so cold, even with all those blankets. The birds woke me up like five times and I kept hearing noises and didn't know what they were. I sat down across from her. Would you want to do that every single night? She shook her head and started crying for real this time, not fake tears, real ones. That man doesn't get to come inside when he's cold.

He came out 20 minutes later, hair still wet, watching me like I was a science experiment. Everything okay fine, I said, your phone went off. He froze mid step. You didn't check it? No. I watched his face fall. He actually looked disappointed. Then he started laughing, this nervous high pitched thing and said it was just a prank. Showed me the text he'd set up with his buddy Marco using a fake contact name. They'd spent a whole week planning it, even created a fake profile picture. I nodded and went back to holding the kids laundry. That's it, he said. No tears, no yelling, no throwing things. I looked at him. My first husband actually cheated with my coworker Harper. I spent six months crying over real betrayal, lost third three pounds, went to therapy for a year and rebuilt my entire life from scratch. You think I'm gonna waste energy on fake drama? His smile vanished completely. That was four weeks ago. The first few days he kept bringing it up. Most wives would have lost it, he said during dinner. Don't you even care? I told him I cared about our kids doctor appointment on Tuesday and the leak under the sink that was costing us $50 a week in water bills. Not, man.

I sat with a weird kid at lunch. By the end of the day, I understood why no one else would. Every school has its own set of unwritten rules. One of these at Goldbrook Middle School was about a 7th grader named Wesley. He sat alone at lunch every single day. Same table in the same corner, same untouched food. Students avoided him. Teachers avoided him. Even the other weird kids wouldn't sit near him. It was my first year teaching, so I didn't understand why everyone avoided him. Like the play egg. Sure, the kid rocked a bowl cut and had dirt under his fingernails, but there were kids still Naruto running in hallways making friends. When I asked around about Wesley, people turned away from me like I just coughed and we were back in 2020. Nobody told me anything about him. They just shook their heads like they were royal monarchs looking down on a peasant. So one day I took it upon myself to grab my tray and walk over to Wesley. Mind if I join you? He didn't look up. You shouldn't be here. He said it like shufu when taowung returned. But I sat down anyway. I'm Mr Davis. I teach eighth grade English. Nothing. He just stared at his sandwich like it had personally wronged him. I tried again. What's your favorite subject, dude? Doesn't matter. I kept trying. Okay, what do you do for fun? Nothing, bro. What do you mean? Nothing. How can one do nothing either way? A group of kids walked past our table. One of them muttered freak, loud enough for Wesley to hear. He didn't react like he was used to it, but I kept trying. I asked about movies, video games, music, yet I got nothing but one word answers in silence. Then Mr Crane walked into the cafeteria. Wesley's whole body went rigid. Mr Crane?

He just sped off and disappeared around the corner. I screamed and ran toward him while I frantically called 9 1 1 for help. He was in critical condition. At the hospital, doctors and nurses rushed in and out every time his vitals crashed while I sat in the waiting room giving my statement to the officials and attending doctor. While it was all still horribly fresh in my head, even when things seem to slow down and stabilize, I couldn't sit still. At first, I felt guilty thinking of all those times I ignored their fights, putting on my headphones and pretending everything was fine when it wasn't. And now Sean was fighting for his life and I couldn't help but imagine the doctors coming out telling me he didn't make it. After an hour of sitting around, a doctor walked over with a grim expression holding the scans. I'm so sorry, he said quietly, but you need to. I looked at the scans bracing myself. But what he showed me was something no one could have ever expected. There wasn't internal bleeding, no swelling, not even a broken bone, just a few fractures and abrasions and a massive aggressive tumor wrapped around his kidney that had absolutely nothing to do with getting Hit by a car. Your brother would have died the moment this started spreading to other organs. It's terrible to say, but he's lucky he ended up here tonight. The doctor said lucky my brother getting run over by my dad.

Was lucky. I wanted to scream at him for using that word, but I couldn't because he was right. A few more weeks and it would have been too late. Sean would have been walking around with a death sentence growing inside him and none of us would have known until it took his life. We need consent for his surgery, he said carefully. I laughed. Consent from who? My mom who's dead or my dad who ran over him or me, a six teen year old kid, I asked bitterly. The doctor's face went awkwardly pale. He ended up getting special permission for the surgery and worked on my brother for 20 hours straight. There were complications. The tumor was worse than expected and we had to remove his entire kidney to prevent the spread. But he's stable now and will be making a full recovery, he told me. When Sean finally woke up, he looked around the room confused. Tubes coming out of everywhere. I'm alive, he asked weakly. You were always a fighter, I whispered, squeezing his hand. I told him everything, the tumor, the surgery, the fact that he would have been dead in months if we hadn't caught it. He just stared at the ceiling for a long time without saying anything. Then he let out a sour laugh. So dad tried to kill me and ended up saving my Life instead, father of the year.

Notting at Nova. Little girls deserve to feel pretty. You're her father, not her mother. Some things you just can't do. I couldn't even respond. I was done failing her. I'd find a salon and pay someone to do her hair every week, whatever it cost. I'd pick up extra shifts to cover it. She deserved better than my clumsy hands and lopsided parts and twist that fell apart by Wednesday. On Sunday, I was about to tell her that we weren't going to do our ritual anymore, that I'd found a better solution for her when she walked into the living room and told me to sit down because she had something for me. She handed me an envelope with my name written on it and her careful handwriting. And my stomach dropped because I was sure she was about to ask me for the same thing. I figured she'd finally worked up the courage to tell me she wanted a real salon instead of me. I opened it and found a printed confirmation from a salon across town called Natural Beauty. It was a registration for an eight week class on braiding and protective styles, covering technique and products and different styles for different occasions. The total cost was $400 and it was marked paid and full. I looked at my nine year old daughter sitting there with her hands folded in her lap and I didn't understand. I asked if she wanted to take the class herself, if she was tired of me doing her hair.

I ring up Susie's regular meal under the school plan. Then we swap identical brown bags real quick. Hers goes home with enough food to feed three kids for dinner. She brings back the empty containers every morning because she insists on keeping them clean for me. The first time I watch that girl actually eat her whole lunch, I cry right there by the milk cooler. She's never looked happier. Then one morning, the principal catches me on the way into work. There's a meeting I need you to attend. Five minutes. I can feel my pulse pounding in my throat. I walk toward the conference room and see the principal standing there with his arms crossed. The staff is already seated. My union rep is in the corner. This is it. I'm getting publicly fired. I step inside and brace myself. Then a bunch of people jump up yelling. Surprise. I'm standing there frozen, completely confused. The principal clears his throat and says another parent complained about the lunch bags. I feel sick. Then he says he pulled Susie aside to ask her directly and she told him everything. My chest tightens. That poor little girl. The principal looks at me and apologizes in front of everyone. I was wrong about you. The school is setting up a donation fund and connecting the family with real resources. Suzie graduated last spring. Then this little boy came through my line and asks me real soft if we have anything that might expire soon. I look at him and smile. Yeah, buddy, I think I got something for you.

Start watching her during my rounds. She picks up her food, never finishes, always looks exhausted. One day I see her glancing around. Then she scrapes her entire lunch into a plastic bag and stuffs it in her backpack. Next day, I ask her straight up about what I saw. Her face goes white. She tells me she's got two younger siblings at home and her mom works nights, so dinner doesn't happen unless Susie makes it happen. She says she can't work the stove yet because she isn't old enough. This nine year old is rationing school lunch to feed her little brother and sister. So that's when I start giving her extra food every time. Only one other kid notices. This girl, who always demands the freshest roll, the biggest slice, throws a fit if her pizza has a bubble on it. She spots Susie with two slices one day and says loud enough for everyone to hear, you're too poor to have two pizza? I'm gonna tell my mom. And I guess she did. Otherwise I wouldn't have ended up in the principal's office. The day after my meeting with the principal, I see Susie come through the line. I can't give her anything extra because the other cafeteria ladies are watching me like Hawks. Susie's smile falls when I hand her the regular tray with one portion. Days go by and I'm watching her not eat. She's getting smaller. Her cheeks are hollowing out. Now I Can't sleep. So one night I stand in my kitchen

Parents, what moment made you realize your child sees everything you try to hide? My daughter Nova lost her mom when she was 3. And nobody warns you when you're a white guy raising a black daughter by yourself that the hair is going to be the thing that breaks you. I had no idea what I was doing those first few years and my wife wasn't there to teach me. I bought products that dried Nova's hair out until it was brittle, brushed it dry and watched chunks break off in my hands. Sent her to preschool with styles that fell apart by snack time. YouTube became my own teacher, but those women made it look so easy and my results never matched. Every Sunday night became our ritual where I'd sit her on the living room floor and attempt to get her hair ready for the school week. She's 9 now and I've gotten better. But better isn't good enough. I can do puffs that stay and I'm working on two strand twists, but they unravel by Wednesday and she comes home with her hair looking rough. The other moms at pickup used to give me sad little smiles, kind that said they could see how hard I was trying and how short I was falling. But lately the smiles have stopped. Now I catch them whispering to each other when they see Nova climb out of the car, their eyes going straight to her hair. Last month, One of them walked right up to me while Nova was getting in the car and said she had a niece who did hair and could give me a good price. I started to thank her for the recommendation when she leaned in closer. It's just not fair to her, she said.

I buy cheap containers from the dollar store and four times the amount of portions for my groceries. And every night when I make myself dinner, I start packing lunch bags with leftovers for Susie and her siblings the next day. For two months, our system works perfectly. Well, trust me, the whole family was on edge. Some wanted to cancel the surprise entirely. Tell pops that Grayson changed his mind. But every single day, pops called me. Only five more days. Only three more days. I can't wait to see what Grayson made for me. His voice was so happy, so hopeful. When Party Day came around. 50 people, we're gathered in the backyard. Pop sat in his favorite chair. Mom beside him, holding his hand. Sixty years of marriage, still looking at him like he hung the moon. Grayson walked to the front of the crowd, laptop in hand. I grabbed my sister's arm. Should we stop him? Too late. The screen lit up. Music started playing. Pop's face appeared. The No. 80 beside it. Then it started counting backwards. 77. Everyone watched in silence. The numbers kept falling. 21 all the way down to ten. Then the slideshow began. A black and white photo appeared. Little pops at 10 years old, standing next to his sister. Both of them gap toothed and grinning. The A I. Made the photo move. Suddenly, pops and his sister were chasing each other, laughing, pushing, being kids. Pops let out a sound I've never heard before. Half laugh, half sob. That's me and Rosie. Rosie died 15 years ago. Now she was alive on the screen, playing with her brother. At 18, pops was graduating high school, cap and gown, holding his diploma up to the camera. The photo Came alive. Made him wave it in the air, pump his fist, grin like the whole world was ahead of him. At 22, their wedding day, pops and mom, black and white. First dance. The AI made them sway together. Her head on his chest, his hand on her back. Young and in love, mom squeezed pops, his hand so tight, her knuckles went white. That's us, she whispered. That's really us. She was tearing up. At 25, he was shipping off to war. Standing at a bus station, duffel bag over his shoulder. Mom crying as she held him. The photo moved. Showed him kissing her forehead, wiping her tears, walking away, looking back.

I've been giving one student extra food for four years and no one else. So I'm standing in the principal's office, right? And I feel like I'm 10 again, getting in trouble for throwing a shoe through a window. I work in the elementary school's cafeteria and ring up the little kids meals. This job is the only thing keeping my lights on since my divorce, and the principal knows it. He's got this smug look on his face telling me some parent complained because their kid came home whining that the lunch lady with hairy hair gives extra dino nuggets and pizza to one girl, but said no when she asked. I touch my blue streaks out of habit. The principal leans back in his chair and says, you're in serious trouble here. A parent is accusing you of favoritism. Not to mention you were caught stealing from the school's food supply. Stealing? Like I'm pocketing chicken tenders for profit. He tells me, if you don't behave perfect from here on out, I'll be forced to fire you. I'm a 43 year old woman being scolded like a child, and I can't say a word back because I need this paycheck more than I need my dignity. I leave his office with my stomach and knots because I know exactly which little Gremlin complained. A few years ago, I noticed this fourth grader named Suzie who always comes through the line dead last. Every day she asks me, do You have any extra food? I'm not allowed to do that. But I start slipping her an extra cookie or milk carton that's about to expire anyway. Then I start watching her during my rounds. She picks at her food. Never

One last time, half the backyard was crying. Now at 28, he came home stepping off the bus thinner, older but alive. Mom was waiting, arms open. The a I made it move showed him dropping his bag, running, lifting her off the ground, spinning her, both of them sobbing into each other's shoulders. Mom buried her face and pops his chest. At 31, the birth of their first child. Pops in the hospital holding a tiny baby looking terrified and proud and overwhelmed all at once. The phone photo came alive showed him rocking the baby gently pressing his lips to her forehead. That baby was me. At 50, his birthday party surrounded by family cake with too many candles. At 58, holding his first grandchild, Grayson. The photo came alive showed pops bouncing baby Grayson on his knee making silly faces. I looked at Grayson standing by the projector, tears running down his face. At 71, pops in a cap and gown again, finally getting his college degree, the one he put off for 50 years while raising a family. The photo moved showed him pumping his fist, the same gesture as his 18 year old self. Same pride, same joy. The video ended on pops at 80, surrounded by everyone he loved. Text appeared on screen. Thank you for believing in me. I love you, pops. Grayson. Silence. Pops stood slowly, tears streaming down his face. He walked straight to Grayson, pulled him into his arms. I Knew it. I knew you were good. Grayson was crying. First time any of us had ever seen it.

Things awkward and uncomfortable for her. I argued with him for, like, 40 minutes. I told him I'd been there since Miguel was 13 years old. I was the one who helped him study for his SAT's. I was the one who drove him to school every morning for three years. David just kept saying his girlfriend felt weird about it and that I needed to respect her boundaries. Finally, I just gave up and agreed not to go. I sent Miguel a long text explaining everything and apologizing for not being able to be there. His reply came back in, like, two minutes. Don't listen to him. You're my mom, and I want you there. Plus, it's not like you have to sit next to him. I don't even know his girlfriend that well. That message broke my heart. Here was this kid who I'd raised, who still called me mom, who wanted me at his graduation. I wasn't going to let David's girlfriend's insecurity ruin his big day. Miguel's other siblings all lived in different states, and none of them were flying in for the graduation. So basically, all he had was David, this random girlfriend, and my family. I told my mom and my sister what was happening. They both immediately said they were coming with me. The day of graduation, we showed up at the high school and found seats on the opposite side of the auditorium from David

My dad burst through my front door with tears in his eyes. I just found out your nephew is planning a special surprise for my 80th birthday. Isn't that wonderful? My stomach dropped. Grayson was 17, had already been suspended twice this year. He bullied kids at his school, harassed elderly teachers. But pops didn't care about that. Grayson was his grandson and he loved him no matter what. Pops squeezed my hand. I know what everyone thinks of him. He had a huge smile on his face, but that boy has always been sweet to me. I know he'll make my birthday unforgettable. I looked at my father, kindest man I've ever known. I couldn't try to shut this down. I'm sure it'll be great, dad. I wanted to believe it, but I knew things even pops didn't like. Last Thanksgiving, when I walked past Grayson's room and saw him watching YouTube videos, public humiliation, pranks, people getting embarrassed in front of crowds, he wasn't just watching either. He was taking notes like he was studying them. A week before granddad's party, my sister called me. Her voice was frantic. I found a folder on Grayson's computer labeled Pops 80th. What's in it? Password protected, but I saw him working on it last night. He kept laughing, rubbing his hands together, saying nobody's ready for what he's planning. I tried confronting Grayson myself. So I hear you're planning something for pops. He just smiled that same smile he had he put Carolina Reaper hot sauce in his five year old cousin's drink. It's gonna be memorable.

I could see him and his girlfriend sitting way across from us. When Miguel's name got called, we all stood up and cheered so loud. After the ceremony ended, Miguel called me immediately. We met up outside and took a bunch of pictures together. Him and his cap and gown with me, my mom and my sister all hugging him. That's when David and his girlfriend walked over. The girlfriend had this really angry look on her face and David looked super uncomfortable. We said goodbye to Miguel and he left with them. Figured that was the end of it. That weekend, Miguel came over to my place like usual and we celebrated his graduation with a cake and presents. That's when he told me what happened. After we left, apparently David's girlfriend completely lost it in the car. She was yelling about how disrespectful it was that we showed up. She said I was trying to stake my claim and make her look bad. David had to spend the whole ride home calming her down. And apparently he even talked badly about me to make her feel better. Before all this, David and I were actually on pretty good terms. We text occasionally about Miguel and could have normal conversations. But now his girlfriend has this huge problem with me. Miguel said David told him he's not allowed to talk to me anymore or see me on weekends.

I went to my former brother in law's graduation even though my ex told me not to. Five years ago when I was 20 and married to my ex husband David, we brought his youngest brother Miguel to the U. S. From Mexico. Miguel had just turned 13 and barely spoke any English. David and I took full legal responsibility for him. I was the one who enrolled him in middle school, sat with him every night helping with homework. I got him English by watching TV shows together. I gave him an allowance, took him shopping for clothes, made sure he ate breakfast before school, all the mom stuff. My own family fell in love with him too. My mom started calling him her grandson. My sister treated him like her nephew. And Miguel started introducing me as his mom to his friends at school because that's what I was to him. When David and I got divorced two years ago, Miguel was devastated. He cried and asked if he still got to see me. I told him of course, nothing was changing between us. So even after the divorce, he'd still come, stay at my apartment on weekends. My new boyfriend doesn't mind at all. He actually really likes Miguel and they play video games together. Last month, Miguel graduated high school. A week before the ceremony, David called me up sounding all serious. his new girlfriend didn't want me or my family at the graduation. He said it would make.

voice_to_text: Thanksgiving dinner, my uncle asked, so what did you end up doing with all that settlement money from your accident? I looked up from my plate. What settlement money? Uncle Frank's smile faded instantly. From the car accident five years ago when that delivery truck ran the red light and you spent three weeks in the hospital, my sister Heather made a strange choking sound. I watched her face drain of all color, turning almost gray under the dining room lighting. I never got any settlement money, I said slowly, a cold feeling spreading through my chest. Still paying off those hospital bills and installments. Uncle Frank put down his wine glass very carefully. Brianna, the insurance company settled for $127,000. I know because I helped your mom with the paperwork when you were still recovering. You were only 17. So it went into a custodial account until you turned eighteen. I turned to my mother, waiting for her to clear up this obvious misunderstanding, but she wouldn't look at me, very interested in cutting her Turkey into impossibly tiny pieces. Mom, my voice came out barely above a whisper. My mind was racing, trying to make the pieces fit together. I turned 18 five years ago. Where did the money go? The silence stretched out forever. I could hear the kitchen faucet dripping in the other room, each drop echoing like a countdown. Gave it to Heather, mom finally whispered, her voice cracking, for her education and getting Started with her life. The words didn't make sense at first. They literally didn't compute in my brain. You gave my money to Heather. I repeated each word coming out separately and distinctly. The money from my accident, from my broken bones and my three weeks in the hospital and my six months of physical therapy. You were getting financial aid for community college, Heather said defensively, her voice shrill and desperate. You didn't need it as much as I did. I had private university tuition and living expenses. I stared at her, actually stared, seeing my sister clearly for maybe the first time in my entire life. Is that where you got your car? The question came out flat and dead. That Audi you bought junior year that you said was from your internship. She didn't answer, but her face answered for her. The apartment downtown you lived in. My voice was getting louder, stronger. The study abroad semester in Paris. The designer clothes you kept posting online. We were going to tell you, mom started weakly when I shouted. Standing up so fast, my chair backward and hit the wall. When exactly were you planning to mention that you stole $127,000 from your daughter who got hit by a truck? The math was simple and devastating. Well, I've been working 40 hours a week at target and going to community college at night, sleeping four hours and living on energy drinks and stress. Heather had been spending my Blood money on her dream life. I called you crying, I said, my voice breaking completely. I called you crying because I couldn't afford my textbooks and you told me to budget better. I was eating Dollar Menu food for dinner while making monthly payments on bills from my own accident. You were always so resilient, Heather said, tears starting to stream down her face. Now you are handling everything fine. Handling it, I repeated the word, tasting like poison in my mouth. I had to drop two classes last semester because I couldn't afford them and work enough hours to pay rent. I've been living in a basement apartment with black mold because it's all I can afford. I haven't been to a dentist in three years. Uncle Frank was doing calculations on his phone, face getting redder by the second. $127,000 plus five years of interest. At even a conservative rate, we're talking about 145,000 to $150,000 in total value you were owed. Mom was sobbing now, but I felt absolutely nothing looking at her tears. She'd had five years to feel guilty, five years to tell the truth. That money was supposed to compensate me for permanent nerve damage in my left leg, I said. My voice deadly calm now. For the nightmares I still have about that truck coming at me, for the fact that I can't run anymore without pain and you gave it away like it was nothing. She's still your sister, mom pleaded. Desperately, no, I said. Clearly, she's a thief who watched me suffer for five years while spending money that belonged to me. That's not a sister. That's a stranger who stole my future. I grabbed my coat from the hallway, my hands surprisingly steady. Now where are you going, mom? Asked her voice small and afraid. To a lawyer, I said simply looking at Uncle Frank, I'm assuming you kept all that paperwork. He nodded grimly. Every document, I'll have it ready tomorrow morning.

My little brother asked why his heart was beating so fast. I was halfway through a raid in my game when Eli wandered into my room, one hand pressed flat against his chest. He was 8 years old and always interrupting me for stupid reasons, so I didn't even pause. Nana, feel this. He grabbed my hand and put it on his chest before I could stop him. His heart was hammering so fast I couldn't count the beats. It felt like a hummingbird trapped inside his ribs. Dude, what were you doing running laps around the house? He shook his head. I was just watching TV. I pulled my hand back and shrugged. You probably just got excited about something. Go drink some water. He stood there for another second looking at me with those big brown eyes, then shuffled back downstairs. I went back to my game. Mom was working a double at the hospital and wouldn't be home until morning. Dad was on a business trip in Seattle. I was 16 and in charge, which mostly meant making sure Eli ate dinner and went to bed on time. Twenty minutes later, he was back. It's still doing it, he said. This time his voice was smaller. I sighed and paused my game for real. Still doing what? The fast thing? It won't slow down. I tried taking deep breaths. Like you said that one time. I hadn't said anything about deep breaths, but I got up anyway. I put my hand on his chest again. Still racing. Feel that fluttering hummingbird feeling. I looked at him more closely. His face was flushed, but his lips looked kind of pale. Does it hurt? He shook his head, then stopped. Kinda like it's squeezing weird. I pulled out my phone and Googled fast heartbeat in kids. The results said anxiety, dehydration, too much sugar, caffeine, normal stuff. I asked Eli if he had any soda. He said no. Any candy? No. Was he nervous about something? He just stared at me. I'm nervous now because my heart won't stop. Fair point. Got him a glass of water and made him sit on the couch. I figured it would pass in a few minutes. Hearts don't just race forever for no reason. Fifteen minutes later, his heart was still pounding. I could see his shirt moving with each beat. That wasn't normal, right? I counted silently, watching the fabric jump. I got to 60 beats and maybe 20 seconds. That math didn't seem right, but I wasn't exactly a doctor. I texted Mom, Eli's heart is beating really fast. Normal. Three dots appeared, then disappear. She was probably with a patient. I looked at my brother. He was sitting very still on the couch. His hand pressed to his chest like he could hold his heart in place. Jenna, I feel weird. Weird how like floaty, like when you stand up too fast. But I'm sitting down. I grabbed my Phone again and searched, fast heartbeat, dizzy child. The first result mentioned something called s V t, super ventricular tachycardia, heart rate over 150 beats per minute. I scrolled faster. It said to call a doctor if symptoms persisted more than a few minutes. We were past that, way past that. My phone buzzed, mom, how fast is he? Pale, dizzy. I typed back, yes to both. It's been like 45 minutes. Her response was immediate. Call 9, 1 1 now. Don't wait. I'm coming. My.

I kicked out my dad's girlfriend after she made a comment about me being racist because I wear a bonnet when I sleep. So my hair is awful, like genuinely awful. It's super thin and curly and every morning I wake up looking like I stuck my finger in an outlet. Giant knots everywhere, hair sticking straight up, frizz for days. My best friend Tori is black and she's seen my morning hair plenty of times. She thinks it's hilarious. Last summer I was complaining about it again and she just shook her head at me. For my birthday two months ago, she gave me a bonnet, the same kind she wears every night. I honestly didn't think it would work for my hair, but I tried it anyway. Dude, game changer. I wake up and my hair is actually manageable now. Way less frizz, barely any knots.
