Christmas dinner, my dad said, you're a burden. You can't live with us anymore. When I packed up and told them I'd stop paying the bills, my dad, at first I thought I misheard. My mom gave this nervous laugh like maybe he was joking. But he just sat there staring at me, waiting for my reaction. The room went silent. My sister Lily froze, her fork halfway to her mouth. She looked at me with wide eyes like she couldn't believe what she just heard. I swallowed the piece of ham I was chewing and put my fork down. What? You heard me? He said, you're no longer welcome here. You need to move out. I just sat there trying to process. I'm 23, have a steady job, could have moved out years ago, but I stayed because they needed me. I, I paid the electric Bill, the internet, groceries most weeks, things they couldn't afford because my dad had been unemployed for years and my mom only worked part time. I wasn't a burden. I was the reason the lights were still on in that house. And now, out of nowhere, I was being kicked out like some useless freeloader. Mom finally spoke up. Maybe we should talk about this later. But dad interrupted. No, Ed, this is my house. I make the rules. And I say, he's done here. Lily put down her fork. She was only 16, and I could tell she was scared. She stared. At our parents like she didn't even recognize them. If they could throw me out so easily, what did that mean for her? I took a deep breath. I wasn't going to argue or beg. If they wanted me out, fine. But they weren't ready for what that really meant. I leaned back in my chair. All right, I said. My dad sat up straighter like he'd won some imaginary battle. My mom still looked uncomfortable, but she didn't say anything. Maybe she was in shock or maybe she, I just didn't care as much as I thought. I stood up, grabbed my plate and carried it to the sink. I didn't want to give them the reaction they wanted. Instead, I looked at Lily, who was still sitting there, tense and confused. I gave her a small nod. She was the only one at that table I still cared about. Dad took a sip of his drink like nothing had happened. Mom went back to picking at her mashed potato. Lilly kept looking at me like she wanted to say something, but she didn't. I didn't stay to finish dinner, just walked out. I went straight to my room, closed the door and started packing. I wasn't going to waste time trying to understand why they were doing this. If they wanted me gone, I was gone. But that also meant they'd lose everything I've been paying for, and I wasn't going to warn them. I packed in silence. But I could hear them talking downstairs. My mom's voice was low and scared. My dad's was firm, like he was trying to convince her of something. I caught bits and pieces. He's old enough. We can handle it. He should have moved out years ago. An hour later, there was a knock on my door. I opened it and Lily slipped inside, quickly shutting the door behind her. Her eyes were red and puffy. She'd been crying. Are you really leaving? She whispered. Yeah. I said, I don't have much choice. Can I come with you? That broke my heart. You're 16, they'd call the cops. But the second you turn 18, my door's open. She hugged me tight. I hate them for that. Don't, I said. Just remember who was here for you. I left that night. Didn't say goodbye to them, just grabbed my stuff and drove to a friend's place. Three days later, my phone exploded. Mom. I stared at the screen.

We were out there for hours. I came home sweaty, exhausted, and still haven't cracked open a single notebook. The night before, I'm sitting at my desk, stacked up, textbooks open, highlighters ready. I'm ready to lock in. Then I remembered I was stuck on this one level in my game. Just one level, I told myself. One level turned into 12. Suddenly it's 2 a. M. I'm half asleep and I've looked at exactly zero pages of notes. Went to bed thinking, well, it's been a good run. Next morning, I drag myself to school running on four hours of sleep and vibe, literally just vibes. No breakfast, no confidence, no clue. I walk into that classroom and everyone's doing last minute cramming. Terrell's flipping through his flashcards like his life depends on it. Another kids rocking back and forth, mumbling formulas. One girl looked like she was about to cry. Test start. I open the booklet. First question, no idea. Second question, also no idea. I'm reading these questions like I've never seen the English language before. Math section, straight guessing. Science, picking answers that sounded right. Reading comprehension. I'm out here choosing based on what I would have done in that situation. If the character seemed chill, I picked C. If they seemed stressed, I went with B. That was my system. 30 minutes in, I'm done. Not because I finished carefully. There's no point staring at questions I don't know. I turned it in and my teacher just looked at me that disappointed headshake that says I'm not even surprised. I went home fully prepared to tell my parents I'm staying in middle school another year, already planning my excuse, my apology speech to continue. Tap the arrow in the bottom right corner and copy the link. Then tap the cap, that icon In the bottom left, finally, click the red button.

Everyone laughed when Dad's will said I inherited nothing of value until they needed what I got. The reading started exactly how my siblings wanted it to. To my eldest son, Steven, I leave $4 million and the Manhattan penthouse. Steven fist bumped like he'd won the lottery, which I guess he had. To my daughter Diana, I leave $4 million in the entire art collection. She was already googling yacht prices. To my son Paul, I leave $4 million in my investment portfolio. Paul whispered yes and high fived Steven. My youngest son, Marcus, I leave the contents of storage unit 47B, which contains nothing of monetary value. The room exploded in laughter. Diana actually snorted champagne. Nothing of monetary value. Oh, my god. Dad had jokes. Paul slapped my shoulder. Hey, maybe it's full of his old golf clubs. Those might be worth 20 bucks. But I noticed something they didn't. The lawyer's hands were trembling as he folded the will. And there was one more envelope with my name on it. I see the key, I asked. More laughter. Steven pulled out his phone to record. This is too good. Marcus opening his inheritance of nothing. The lawyer handed me a small key and the envelope. Your father insisted you read this privately, probably an apology letter, Diana shrieked. Sorry you were born last. I pocketed both and stood up. Three years of being Dad's sole caregiver during cancer, three years of running the family construction empire while they partied. In Europe and I got nothing of value. Wait, Paul called out, suddenly serious. We need you to keep running the company. We'll pay you a salary, 65 k, Steven added. That's generous for someone with no ownership. Very generous. Diana agreed, considering you just inherited nothing. I walked out without a word. That night, I opened envelope first. Dad's handwriting shakier than I remembered. Son, they think value only means money. Check the unit, then wait for them to call. Dash Dad Storage unit 47B was stuffed with filing cabinets, old ones from the 1970s. I opened the first drawer and my heart stopped. Every original contract, every patent, every client relationship agreement, every single document that proved ownership of anything in our company. But that wasn't the kicker.

My sister used to cover my ears at night. I now know the disgusting reason why. When I was seven years old, my older sister Emma, started sneaking into my room every night. She'd wait until I was asleep, then she'd press her hands over my ears and hold them there for hours. I'd wake up sometimes and ask what she was doing. She'd always say the same thing. I'm protecting you. Go back to sleep. I never understood what she meant, but every morning, she'd be gone and my ears would ache. This went on for three years. Every single night from age 7 to 10. Then suddenly it stopped. Emma moved away to college, and I never saw her do it again. I'm 32 now. Emma died last week in a car accident. A funeral. My aunt pulled me aside and said, your sister asked me to give you this if anything happened to her. She handed me a sealed envelope. Inside was a letter in Emma's handwriting. If you're reading this, I'm gone. And now you need to know the truth about why I covered your ears all those years. I wasn't protecting you from something outside. I was protecting you from something inside our house. Something that only came out at night. My hands started shaking. I kept reading. When you were seven, I started hearing voices at night. Not from outside. From the walls, from the floor, from the ceiling. They were whispering. Hundreds of Voices, all talking at once. I couldn't understand what they were saying, but I knew they were talking about you. I felt sick. Emma had never mentioned hearing voices. I went to mom and dad, but they said I was dreaming. They said I was making it up for attention. But I knew what I heard. And the voices got louder every night. They were saying your name over and over, like they were calling you. The letter continued. One night, I followed the voices. They LED me to the basement, to the door that's always locked. The door dad told us never to open. I found the key in his desk, and I opened it. I remembered that door. It was in the corner of the basement behind some old boxes. I asked my parents about it when I was a kid, but they said it was just storage. Behind the door was a staircase going down, way down. I counted 47 steps before I reached the bottom. And what I found there made me understand why the voices wanted you. I stopped reading. I didn't want to know. But I forced myself to continue. There was a room. A big room with symbols painted on the walls. And in the center was a circle drawn in something dark. Something that looked like dried blood. Inside the circle were photos. Dozens of them. All of you. From the day you were born until that week. Someone had been taking Photos of you your entire life. My stomach turned. I kept reading. I looked closer and saw writing under the photos. Dates. And next to each date was a number. I didn't understand what they meant until I saw the last photo. It was from that morning. And next to it was written, day 2 5:57. Final phase begins tonight. 2,557 days. I did the math. That would have been right around the time I turned 7. I ran upstairs, and that's when I realized what the voices were doing.

My boyfriend blindfolded me and said, trust me. After 3 exes who destroyed that word, I was terrified. I hate surprises. Hate them. My first boyfriend's surprise was forgetting our anniversary and pretending the gas station flowers he grabbed on the way over were planned. He handed them to me still wrapped in plastic with the price tag on. My second boyfriend surprise was a trip to Vegas. I, I was so excited until I found out it was for his buddy's bachelor party. I spent three days holding purses while they got drunk at clubs. My third boyfriend's surprise was the worst. He broke up with me at my own birthday dinner right after the waiter brought out the cake. He said he didn't want to ruin my birthday by doing it before, so he waited until dessert, like that was better. So when Jordan left a blindfold on my pillow and told me to clear my Saturday, every alarm in my body went off. We've been dating two years. Good years, really good years. But I had good years before. Good years don't mean anything when the bad day finally comes. Just trust me, he said. Guiding me into his car. I wanted to. I really did, but my hands wouldn't stop shaking. The drive took 40 minutes. I tried guessing where we were by the turns and the sounds outside a highway for a while, then smaller roads, then gravel. Nothing made sense. When the car finally Stopped and he helped me out. I heard birds, lots of them, chirping, squawking, whistling. It sounded like we were in a jungle. He pulled off the blindfold. We were standing in front of the city aviary. I blinked at the sign, not understanding at first. Then I remembered I'd mentioned this place once be six months ago. I saw a flyer at a coffee shop and said it looked cool, just a passing comment while we waited for our lattes. I didn't think he was even listening. He was on his phone. You remembered, I whispered. Jordan grinned, but there was something nervous in his eyes. Two years with you, I pay attention. None of my exes ever paid attention, not once. I wanted to cry right there in the parking lot. Inside was magical. Families filled the seats. Kids pointed at bird cages along the walls. Parakeets chirped, a macaw squawked somewhere. A cockatoo whistled a little tune. We found seats in the middle and I couldn't stop smiling. But Jordan kept fidgeting, checking his phone, adjusting his collar, bouncing his leg. The old fear crept back. What if this was the setup for Bad News? What if he brought me somewhere beautiful so I couldn't make a scene when he dumped me? My third boyfriend did that, picked a nice restaurant so I'd be too embarrassed to cry. What if Jordan was doing the same thing? I started picking at my nails, a nervous habit I'd had. Since I was a kid. A woman in khaki pants stepped onto the stage with a grey pigeon on her arm. Good afternoon, everyone. This is Percy. He's a messenger pigeon. Hold up a Bill and Percy takes it. Then he brings back a special note. Think of it as the world's most expensive fortune cookie. The crowd laughed. A little girl went first. Percy swooped down, gentle as a feather, took her dollar and flew back. Her note said, adventure awaits. She beamed at her mom. An older man tried next. His said, wisdom grows with age. He chuckled and showed his wife. Jordan nudged my arm. You should try. I don't know. Come on for me. He was still fidgeting, still nervous. But something in his voice made me reach into my purse. I found a five dollar Bill and held it up. Percy's head turned toward me. He launched from his perch and landed on my armrest, talked his head like he was studying me. Then he took the Bill so gently it felt like a kiss. He flew back to his cage. The woman retrieved a scroll tied with white ribbon and walked it over to me. That seemed odd. The others have been read out loud from the state. This one's special, she said with a wink. My hands trembled as I untied the ribbon. The scroll was longer than the others, real Parchment. I unrolled it slowly. The handwriting was Jordan's, my dearest love. From the moment you stole my heart, like Percy stole that Bill, I knew you were the one. I know surprises scare you. I know people have let you down, but I'm not them. I see you, I hear you. I remember the little things because to me, nothing about you is little. Will you marry me? I read it three times. Ears blurred the words. I turned to Jordan. He wasn't in his seat anymore. He was on one knee in the aisle holding a small velvet box. I know you've been hurt, he said. His voice cracked, but I'm not going anywhere. I'm just asking you to let me love you forever. A little kid in the front row whispered loud enough for everyone to hear. Is she gonna say yes? I laughed through my tears a thousand times. Yes. The ring caught the light as we walked out hand in hand. Percy had delivered a lot of messages, but I like to think ours was his favourite.

I told my autistic nephew that he deserves every bit of bullying he's getting at school. Caleb was the sweetest kid I'd ever known. 11 years old, autistic, heart of absolute gold. He had a pet goldfish named bubbles that he talked to every morning. Would stand there in his pajamas telling her about his dreams before school. He was obsessed with anime. Could name every character from My Hero Academia. Talk your ear off about it if you let him. But the thing that got me most was how he treated people at family gatherings. He'd run around giving everyone hugs. Not the obligatory kind. Real ones, tight ones. Like he meant it. If someone was sitting alone, he noticed, walk right over and sit next to them. Wouldn't even say anything sometimes. Just be there for them. I adored that kid more than anything. Then last Thanksgiving happened. Caleb pulled me into the hallway careful so his parents wouldn't notice tears streaming down his face. Uncle, I need to tell you something. His chest was heaving. That rapid rise and fall when someone is crying and hyperventilating at once. I'm getting bullied in school. He told me about these two kids, a boy and a girl. They wouldn't leave him alone. They knocking his anime books out of his hands, calling him names, stealing his peanut butter jelly sandwiches. Sometimes they even shoved him into lockers. I held him while he cried. Have you told your mom and Dad? I asked gently. He nodded. They told me big boys deal with bullying themselves. They told me to figure out how to stop it alone. I watched anime with him until he calmed down. Then I found his parents in the kitchen. Did you. You know Caleb's being bullied? His mom. My sister barely looked up from her mashed potatoes. Kids are mean. He needs to toughen up. His dad shrugged at me. He's exaggerating. You know how Caleb gets. I was stunned. He was sobbing. This seems serious. My sister swatted at the air like I was being ridiculous. We'll handle it, she said. Don't worry about it. Then they changed the subject. Weeks went by. I kept checking in on Caleb, texting and calling him every day. Each time, he seemed a little dimmer, quiet. By the time Christmas came, Caleb walked into the family gathering and didn't hug anyone. All the light had been bullied out of him. While the other kids played and even discussed anime, he sat in the corner alone, staring at nothing. I pulled my sister aside. Something is seriously wrong. Why aren't you doing anything? She snapped. I said, drop it! This is none of your business. I didn't understand. Why were they being like this? Their son was falling apart. Caleb had even stopped taking care of bubbles. The light behind his eyes was gone. I couldn't just watch anymore. I called my sister next week, said I wanted to Pick Caleb up from school, take him for ice cream. She hesitated, then agreed. My real plan was to see and confront these bullies myself. I got to the school on the Friday a few minutes after the bell. Saw Caleb walking out alone, the only kid not picked up yet. I started walking towards him. Then suddenly, two kids stepped in front of him. A boy and a girl. His bullies. The boy shoved his shoulder hard. I picked up speed, marching right at them, ready to end this. Then the girl said something super loud. Loud enough for me to hear, aimed at Caleb. You think we forgot about Sophie? You think anyone's gonna forget about her? I froze. Caleb had never told me about a Sophie. Caleb saw me and ran over. Can we go, please? He started dragging me away, but the girl caught up before we could go. I noticed her eyes were red and puffy, not the eyes of a bully. She was yelling. Sophie never got the chance to run. I looked at her. I dared myself to ask, who's Sophie? The girl stared at me like I was stupid. You seriously don't know? I shook my head. She pulled out her phone, brought it closer to me. I felt Caleb trying to drag me away, but something in me told me I should look at the phone. So I did. A photo of a small girl with down syndrome, smiling, holding a Stuffed rabbit. The girl started talking again. Sophie's my best friend. But she can't come to school anymore because of Caleb. That's when the boy stepped forward. Your nephew's messed up, dude. He used to harass Sophie all the time. Pinch her and take her stuff. And make fun of how she walks. The girl's voice cracked. She can't even talk. She couldn't tell anyone. I felt sick. I looked down at Caleb. He'd stop trying to drag me away. The girl's voice broke. Then he followed Sophie into the bathroom with his iPad. Recorded her and showed everyone. Silence. Try to hang herself with her jumping rope. After that, the boy. The school didn't do anything because he's autistic. His parents know, but won't do anything. The girl wiped her face. So, yeah, we push him because nobody else will do anything. I turned around. Caleb was staring at the ground. The car ride home was silent. I pulled into the driveway. Is it true? I asked Caleb. Nothing. What you did to that girl, is it true? Silence. Look at me. He turned. But his face wasn't sad, wasn't sorry. It was blank. Empty. That's when I realised. The nice kid act was all fake. I stared at him for a long time. You deserve it. He blinked. Everything they're doing to you. You deserve all of it. I unlocked the doors. Get out!

An oh shit moment where you realized you've been doing something the wrong way for years. I worked at the same insurance office for almost 10 years. Every single morning I'd stop at Jerry's Coffee on Fifth Street, order my usual black coffee and add what I thought was cream from the self serve station. My co workers always made fun of how strong and bitter my coffee was. They'd take one sip and make faces like I was drinking motor oil. How do you drink that garbage? My, my desk mate Ashley would say, watching me gulp down my morning cup, I just laugh and tell her I liked my coffee with character, strong and bold, just like me. The whole office knew about my weird coffee preference. Even during meetings, people would joke about how I could probably strip paint with whatever I was drinking. For almost a decade, this was my routine. Same coffee shop, same order, same weird looks from everyone who tried it. I thought I just had different taste buds or something. Maybe I was just tougher than everyone else when it came to bitter drinks. Then one Tuesday morning, Jerry's Coffee was closed for kitchen repairs. A handwritten sign on the door said they'd be back in a week. I panicked a little because I'm not great with change. But I spotted another coffee place just two blocks down called bean. There I walked in and ordered my usual black coffee. Please, the young Barista with purple hair smiled and handed me the cup. Then I asked for cream on the side, just like I always did at Jerry's. She pointed to a small metal pitcher next to the sugar packet. I poured in my usual amount and took that first sip. My mouth almost dropped open. The coffee was smooth, creamy, actually enjoyable to drink. Instead of feeling like punishment, maybe this place just had really good coffee beans or something. When Jerry's reopened the next week, I went back to my normal routine. But something was bugging me. Now, why did that other place taste so different? Was their coffee really that much better? I decided to pay closer attention to what I was doing. I walked up to the self serve.

That bridesmaid who got hot. And my best friend tried to kick me out of her wedding because of it. When Riley asked me to be her maid of honor, I cried. We've been best friends since sophomore year of college. The kind of friends who knew each other's coffee orders and Netflix passwords. She'd always been the gorgeous one, the one guys noticed first when we walked into bars. I was the funny sidekick who made everyone laugh when conversations got awkward. I was fine with it. That was just our thing. She got engaged, Connor, in February, and the wedding was set for October, eight months away. When she handed me the bridesmaid dress options at her apartment, she hesitated before saying, so these run pretty small. The designer only goes up to a size 16. And you're like an 18 or 20, right? She said it so casually, like she was commenting on the weather. Maybe we could get you a personal trainer as an early birthday gift. I know this amazing guy named Dominic who works at APEX Fitness downtown. Got my cousin Rachel into crazy good shape. I felt my face get hot, but I smiled and said, sure. She venmoed me $800 that night with a note for Dominic. You're gonna look so good. I met Dominic the next Monday. He was brutal. Six days a week, 5:00am. Full body torture sessions that left me barely able to walk to my car. He put Me on 1,400 calories a day. Mostly grilled protein and vegetables. No alcohol, no. No sugar. No excuses. I started tracking everything in this app called My Plate. I canceled plans so I could meal prep. I stopped going to happy hours. My co workers asked if I was okay because I turned down birthday cake three times. But something clicked. For the first time in my life, I felt in control. By June, I'd lost 40 pounds. By September, I'd lost 70. My face had cheekbone. My collarbone showed. I bought jeans in a size 6, a size I'd never even touched in a store before. I felt like I'd unlocked a secret level of life I didn't know existed two weeks before.

Because I was born deformed, in my father's eyes, I wasn't even worth as much as a pig. So he sold me to a witch. That day, a woman who came to buy pigs stared at my dirty face and casually asked my father, how much for this creature? Six for. What are you doing? Sold for four marks! Have you lost your mind? You can't give her to them! As I said, sold for four marks. Terrified, I begged my mother to save me. But my father held me down so hard, couldn't even move. Just like that, I was treated like freight. And hand it over to a stranger, a woman who turned out to be the witch to SEIA. She brought me to eritusa, a place they called a sanctuary of magic. That night, I saw myself in a mirror for the very first time. Ugly, twisted, almost not human. Shame and despair surged inside me. I smashed the mirror with my fist, grabbed a sharp shard with shaking hands, and tried to end a life that felt pointless. But I couldn't. Couldn't even die. The next day, I woke up in Eritrea's Grand Hall with Toseia standing beside me. Shaking with hatred, I clenched my teeth and asked her, do I not even have the right to die? That's adorable, piglet. You weren't taking control. You were losing it. In the end, toseya said she wanted to teach me magic. Magic to someone who didn't even Think life was worth living

Riley's Q was coming whether she could breathe or not. And Riley started coughing, not normal coughing. These e violent spasms that sounded like she was choking on her own lungs. Her whole body convulsed with each cough. She coughed so hard she threw up this in stream of bile that flattered on the concrete floor between her hands. Bega didn't even flinch. He just stepped back slightly to avoid getting anything on his shoes. My mom lost it completely. If you don't call an ambulance right now, I will sue this school for every single dollar it has. Go ahead and try, Vegas said calmly. He grabbed Riley under her arms and held her upright like she was a prop. He needed to move. She's going on stage. Riley's legs barely held her. Her face had gone from flush to this grayish color that terrified me. She was still wheezing with every breath. That high pitched whistle that meant her airways were closing. The stage manager's voice came through the headset system 30 seconds to Riley's entrance. Missus Chen was crying. Now, please, please don't do this. Vega ignored her. He positioned Riley at the wing entrance, holding her upright with one hand on her shoulder. Through the gap in the curtain, I could see the stage, the bright lights, the actor finishing his monologue, the audience of 300 people waiting for their lead actress. 20 seconds, the stage manager called. Riley tried to pull away but didn't have The strength, she was using every ounce of energy just to breathe. My mom lunged forward, but Vega blocked her with his body. Touch me and I'll have you removed for disrupting a school function. 10 seconds. Riley's wheezing suddenly got quieter, not better, worse. When an asthma attack, it's quiet. It means almost no air is moving. I knew that from the last time we'd rushed her to the E R. 5 seconds. Vega tightened his grip on Riley's shoulder, positioning her for her entrance. The actor on stage delivered his final line. The music swelled. Riley's cue. And that's when my mom did something that made Principal Vega's face go white. Rest of the story is linked below and on my channel.

The principal told the whole auditorium my sister was overreacting to her breathing condition and made her finish the performance. While 300 students watched my sister Riley collapsed backstage during the spring musical. Not a graceful stage fall. She went down hard, gasping like she couldn't pull air into her lungs. I was helping with tech crew when I heard the thud. Riley was on her knees, one hand clutching her inhaler, the other braced against the wall. Her lips had that bluish tint I'd seen before during bad asthma attacks. Missus Chen, the drama teacher, rushed over. Riley, honey, can you breathe? Riley shook her head, tears streaming. She managed to use her inhaler, but nothing changed. She was wheezing so loud, I could hear it over the opening number playing on stage. Call 9 1 1, I said already, pulling out my phone. Principal Vega appeared out of nowhere and grabbed my wrist. Absolutely not. We have 300 people out there who paid for tickets. Missus Chen looked up from where she was crouched next to Riley. She's having a severe asthma attack. She needs medical attention. She's anxious. Vega cut her off. Opening night jitters. I've seen it 100 times. Crouch next to Riley with his fake concerned expression. You're the lead, sweetheart. Everyone's counting on you. Just take some deep breaths and get back out there. Riley tried to seek, but could only wheeze. The sound was getting worse. Higher pitch, more strained. My mom pushed Through the backstage curtain. She'd been sitting in the third row and somehow knew something was wrong. She took one look at Riley and went pale. She needs a hospital now. Vegas stood up, physically blocking her path to Riley. Missus Hoffman, I understand your concern, but this is a school event and I'm in charge. Your daughter signed a commitment contract. We've sold out three nights. The show must go on. Are you insane? Look at her. Riley was leaning forward now, propped on her hands, using her arms to help her breathe. It's called tripod positioning. A classic sign. And asthma attack is getting danger. I'd Learned that after her last er visit. Missus Chen tried again, her voice shaking. Principal Vega, I really think we should. She goes on in 90 seconds, he said flatly. The curtain call for Act 1 is already running. Her entrance is huge. Get her on her feet. I could see the stage manager through the wings, headset on, counting down with her fingers. 60 seconds.

voice_to_text: Those warm days vanished in a heartbeat and suddenly it was time to say goodbye. Nick slipped Ella a small scrap of paper, his home address scribbled in his familiar handwriting. That tiny note instantly became a lifeline between them. As she watched Nick prepare to head straight into the battlefield, her eyes shimmered with longing. His buddies hoisted her up on their shoulders so she could reach him. And right there under everyone's gaze, they shared a kiss soaked in fear, hope and desperate love. Ella felt her chest hollow out as he pulled away. A wave of loneliness swept through her before she even realized it. After they were married, Ella finally gained the high quality medical benefits she'd been hoping for and their bond kept growing stronger through constant messages. Even in the middle of war zones, Nick always carved out a moment to text her little pieces of his life. Between missions, Ella sent back her own world in return. Every morning she snapped a picture of the first sunrise she saw, sending that calm, golden beauty across thousands of miles to him. Eventually, they upgraded to video calls and every time their eyes met through the screen, it felt like their hearts were side by side. Until one day Nick called again. But this time his face was pale and his voice carried a weight she'd never heard before. We almost lost a man today, he told her quietly. The whole team was crushed. Ella Felt panic coiled tight inside her. Meanwhile, the cocktails she crafted at the bar were gaining serious popularity. For the first time, she could fully support herself. But peace didn't. Last phone call from the military shattered it in seconds. Nick had been injured during a mission. Ella's heart clenched so hard it hurt. She grabbed the address Nick once gave her and rushed to tell his father what had happened. The entire family headed straight to the hospital. To her shock, the first thing Nick said when he saw her was a scolding. You shouldn't have told them. Now they're worried sick. And before she could respond, the man pulled from the flames was still hanging on.

voice_to_text: To honor her late boyfriend's final wish, the girl climbs a tower that seems to scrape the edge of space. She scales tens of thousands of meters with nothing but grit and heartbreak driving her forward. At the summit, she releases his ashes into the open sky, letting them swirl in the winds far above the world. But the moment they turn to head back, latter snaps clean off without warning. Her friend lunges just in time, catching the safety rope before the girl plunges into the void. It's a razor thin escape from certain death, but her friend's strength alone isn't nearly enough to haul her back. So he wraps the rope around a metal post and begins inching her upward muscles trembling with every pull. Just when she thinks she's about to be saved, her friend reacts fast, yanking with everything he's got. His relentless effort pays off as the girl finally grips the last remaining piece of ladder above. She climbs shaking back onto the platform. Both of them are left breathless, shaken to the core. But the nightmare isn't over. Aside from a tiny piece at the top, the entire ladder has crashed down. They're now stranded at a mind numbing, impossible height. In panic, they try their phones. Nothing. No signal this high up. Then luck kicks in. They discover an emergency kit inside binoculars and a flare gun. For a moment, hope flickers back to life. But reality hits hard. The desert below is Empty, endless, lifeless. Still, her friend keeps scanning the horizon, refusing to quit. Finally, she spots an old, half dead RV in the distance. Sadly, it looks completely abandoned by now. They've been trapped for over five brutal hours. Desert Sun is scorching them alive. Suddenly, her friend gets an idea. She types out a desperate SOS message, ties the phone to the rope, and lowers it carefully, hoping it'll catch a signal below. But when they haul it back up, the message still hasn't gone through. Even so, her friend refuses to quit. She decides to throw the phone all the way down. They wrap it in layers of clothing, tuck it inside a shoe, and send it plummeting. When the shoe hits the ground intact, they finally breathe again. And that's when they see him.

voice_to_text: The guy wanted to be close to the girl he liked, so he deliberately shoved Jack aside. After pushing Jack away, he laid down next to gray.
